05715nam a22009375i 9780231551786DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019032664  a97802315517867 a10.7312/baer196702doi  a(DE-B1597)550736  a(OCoLC)1119063899  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHQ75.8.M326bA3 2020 4aHQ75.8.M326 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a306.76/62092aB2231 aBaer, Marc David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGerman, Jew, Muslim, Gay :bThe Life and Times of Hugo Marcus /cMarc David Baer. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion, Culture, and Public Life ;v4200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Fighting for Gay Rights in Berlin, 1900– 1925 -- t2. Queer Convert: Protestant Islam in Weimar Germany, 1925– 1933 -- t3. A Jewish Muslim in Nazi Berlin, 1933– 1939 -- t4. Who Writes Lives: Swiss Refuge, 1939– 1965 -- t5. Hans Alienus: Yearning, Gay Writer, 1948– 1965 -- tConclusion: A Goethe Mosque for Berlin -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHugo Marcus (1880–1966) was a man of many names and many identities. Born a German Jew, he converted to Islam and took the name Hamid, becoming one of the most prominent Muslims in Germany prior to World War II. He was renamed Israel by the Nazis and sent to the Sachsenhausen concentration camp before escaping to Switzerland. He was a gay man who never called himself gay but fought for homosexual rights and wrote queer fiction under the pen name Hans Alienus during his decades of exile.In German, Jew, Muslim, Gay, Marc David Baer uses Marcus’s life and work to shed new light on a striking range of subjects, including German Jewish history and anti-Semitism, Islam in Europe, Muslim-Jewish relations, and the history of the gay rights struggle. Baer explores how Marcus created a unique synthesis of German, gay, and Muslim identity that positioned Johann Wolfgang von Goethe as an intellectual and spiritual model. Marcus’s life offers a new perspective on sexuality and on competing conceptions of gay identity in the multilayered world of interwar and postwar Europe. His unconventional story reveals new aspects of the interconnected histories of Jewish and Muslim individuals and communities, including Muslim responses to Nazism and Muslim experiences of the Holocaust. An intellectual biography of an exceptional yet little-known figure, German, Jew, Muslim, Gay illuminates the complexities of twentieth-century Europe’s religious, sexual, and cultural politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aEurope-Ethnic relations-History-20th century. 0aGay menzGermanyvBiography. 0aGay men-Germany-Biography. 0aHolocaust survivorszGermanyvBiography. 0aHolocaust survivors-Germany-Biography. 0aJewszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aJews-Europe-History-20th century. 0aMarcus, Hugo,-1880-1966. 0aMuslim converts from JudaismzGermanyvBiography. 0aMuslim converts from JudaismzGermanyxBiography. 0aMuslim converts from Judaism-Germany-Biography. 0aMuslimszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aMuslims-Europe-History-20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz97831